    "narrative": "The focus for Ghost Ride the WHIP today centers on capitalizing on speed-favorable matchups, with **Mickey Moniak** (75.98) and **Corbin Carroll** (69.14) serving as our primary offensive engines against Freddy Peralta and Bubba Chandler, respectively. **Mickey Moniak** benefits immensely from the park factor\u2014playing in a hitter-friendly environment\u2014while his leadoff spot and platoon advantage drive his elite efficiency score. Similarly, **Corbin Carroll** is a lock despite the SP skill deficit, as his dynamic platoon edge and top-of-order security make him essential for our SB-weighted mandate. **James Wood** (69.03) rounds out our high-floor tier; his 0.377 xwOBA and leadoff position against Taj Bradley create a high-leverage environment for counting stats. We are also leaning on **Seiya Suzuki** (68.17) and **Vinnie Pasquantino** (67.53), both of whom are buoyed by favorable SP matchups and strong lineup placement, allowing them to remain comfortably in the \"Strong\" start category.\n\nWhile the depth is solid, the decision to bench **Austin Riley** (47.57) was the most difficult pivot of the day. Despite his pedigree, **Austin Riley** faces a formidable matchup against George Kirby, and the optimizer favored the platoon-advantaged upside of **Vinnie Pasquantino** and the speed-dependent utility of **Brice Turang** (65.04). **Brice Turang** remains a tactical start specifically due to his 85% stolen base probability against a slower delivery from Andre Pallante, which provides more category value than the raw power floor of **Austin Riley**. We must remain vigilant regarding the \"Lineup Pending\" status for all players; notably, **Tyler Soderstrom** (43.82) is operating near the bottom of our threshold. While the wind-out conditions at his park provide a slight bump, his negative SP skill adjustment makes him a candidate to be swapped if official lineups move him further down the order. Finally, keep an eye on **Kyle Karros** (48.01); he sits in a precarious spot, and while his park advantage is substantial, the threat of an elite arm like Freddy Peralta keeps his floor dangerously close to our benching threshold.",
